'''Jean Baptiste Marie Franceschi-Delonne''' ([[1767]] - [[October 23]] [[1810]], [[Carthagena]]) was a [[France|French]] General, who served throughout the [[French Revolutionary Wars: Campaigns of 1796|Revolutionary campaign on the Rhine]], took part in the [[French Revolutionary Wars: Campaigns of 1799|campaign of Zurich]] in [[1799]], and distinguished himself very greatly by his escape from, and subsequent return to, [[Genoa]], when in [[1800]] [[Mass<U+00E9>na]] was closely besieged in that city. He became a [[cavalry]] colonel in [[1803]], was promoted general of [[brigade]] on the field of [[Battle of Austerlitz|Austerlitz]], and served in southern [[Italy]] and in [[Spain]] on the staff of King [[Joseph Bonaparte]]. During the [[Peninsular War]] he won great distinction as a cavalry general, and in [[1810]] Napoleon made him a baron. At this time he was a prisoner in the hands of the Spaniards. into whose hands he had fallen while bearing important despatches during the [[Battle of Talavera de la Reina|campaign of Talavera]]. He was harshly treated by his captors, and died at Carthagena on the 23rd of October 1810.

